{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476274"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13717"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13717"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.27,0.41,0.18,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6336"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87334"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6336"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44165"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87334"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a sudden onset of sharp chest pain and shortness of breath for the past two hours. He is a tall basketball player with no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is decreased breath sounds on the right side of the chest. A chest X-ray confirms the presence of a right-sided pneumothorax with a 3 cm rim of air between the lateral lung edge and the chest wall at the level of the hilum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge with follow-up in one week","Immediate needle decompression","Admission for observation and oxygen therapy","Insertion of a chest tube","Oral antibiotics and outpatient follow-up"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor a patient with a moderate to large-sized spontaneous pneumothorax and minimal symptoms, the most appropriate management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmission for observation and oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E. In children over 12 years, a pneumothorax is considered \u0027large\u0027 if the distance between the lateral lung edge and chest wall at the level of the hilum is \u003E2 cm, which is the case here (3 cm). However, the clinical status of the patient is more important than the size of the pneumothorax in determining management. This patient is clinically stable with only minimal symptoms, making conservative management appropriate. High-flow oxygen therapy should be administered even though the patient\u0027s oxygen saturation is normal, as it creates a diffusion gradient that accelerates the reabsorption of the pneumothorax by reducing the partial pressure of nitrogen in the pleural space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate needle decompression\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for a tension pneumothorax, which is not described in this scenario. The patient is stable with only minimal symptoms, despite the large size of the pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsertion of a chest tube\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary if the patient\u0027s condition worsens or if there is no improvement with conservative management, but it is not the first step for a clinically stable patient, even with a large pneumothorax. The decision to insert a chest tube should be based on clinical status rather than size alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge with follow-up in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for a large pneumothorax, as it requires closer monitoring and potential intervention. Even though the patient is stable, admission is warranted to ensure safety and monitor for potential progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics and outpatient follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E are not relevant to the management of a spontaneous pneumothorax, as this condition is not typically associated with infection. Antibiotics play no role in the management of uncomplicated pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of pneumothorax in young, tall individuals is particularly important as they are at higher risk of recurrence. While this initial episode is managed conservatively with observation and oxygen therapy, the patient should be counselled about the risk of recurrence and potential need for definitive treatment (e.g., pleurodesis) if recurrences occur. Close monitoring during admission is crucial to ensure that any clinical deterioration is promptly addressed, which may necessitate more invasive interventions if required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In children over 12 years, a pneumothorax is considered \u0027large\u0027 if the distance between the lateral lung edge and chest wall at the level of the hilum is \u003E2 cm.","Patients with a moderate-sized spontaneous pneumothorax and minimal symptoms should be admitted for observation and oxygen therapy.","The clinical status of the patient is more important than the size of the pneumothorax in determining management.","High-flow oxygen therapy accelerates pneumothorax absorption by creating a diffusion gradient, even in patients with normal oxygen saturation."],"references":["Primary Spontaneous Pneumothorax. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Clinical Guideline [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Primary_spontaneous_pneumothorax/","MacDuff A, Arnold A, Harvey J Management of spontaneous pneumothorax: British Thoracic Society pleural disease guideline 2010. Thorax. 2010;65:ii18-ii31."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13717"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71591"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-27T14:42:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-27T14:44:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6336"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87334"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt